"prompt": Define two points (x0,y0) and (x1,y1) of the plane to be equivalent if y0−x0=y1−x1. Check that this is an equivalence relation and describe the equivalence classes.
"output": To determine whether the relation \( R \) defined by \((x_0, y_0) R (x_1, y_1)\) if \( y_0 - x_0 = y_1 - x_1 \) is an equivalence relation, we need to verify that the relation satisfies three properties: reflexivity, symmetry, and transitivity.

### Reflexivity
A relation is reflexive if every element is related to itself. That is, for any point \((x_0, y_0)\), we need to show that \((x_0, y_0) R (x_0, y_0)\).

Calculating:
\[ y_0 - x_0 = y_0 - x_0 \]
This is clearly true, so the relation is reflexive.

### Symmetry
A relation is symmetric if whenever an element \( a \) is related to an element \( b \), then \( b \) is also related to \( a \). For our relation, if \((x_0, y_0) R (x_1, y_1)\), we need to check if \((x_1, y_1) R (x_0, y_0)\) is also true.

Given:
\[ y_0 - x_0 = y_1 - x_1 \]
Since equality is symmetric:
\[ y_1 - x_1 = y_0 - x_0 \]
Thus, \((x_1, y_1) R (x_0, y_0)\) is true, and so the relation is symmetric.

### Transitivity
A relation is transitive if whenever an element \( a \) is related to an element \( b \), and \( b \) is related to an element \( c \), then \( a \) is also related to \( c \). For our relation, if \((x_0, y_0) R (x_1, y_1)\) and \((x_1, y_1) R (x_2, y_2)\), then we must show \((x_0, y_0) R (x_2, y_2)\).

Given:
\[ y_0 - x_0 = y_1 - x_1 \quad \text{and} \quad y_1 - x_1 = y_2 - x_2 \]
By the transitive property of equality:
\[ y_0 - x_0 = y_2 - x_2 \]
Thus, \((x_0, y_0) R (x_2, y_2)\) is true, and the relation is transitive.

### Conclusion on Equivalence Relation
Since the relation satisfies reflexivity, symmetry, and transitivity, it is indeed an equivalence relation.

### Equivalence Classes
The equivalence class of a point \((x_0, y_0)\) under this relation consists of all points \((x, y)\) such that \( y - x = y_0 - x_0 \). This relation can be rearranged to:
\[ y - x = k \quad \text{where} \quad k = y_0 - x_0 \]
Thus, the equivalence class of \((x_0, y_0)\) is the set of all points \((x, y)\) that lie on the line \( y = x + k \) in the plane.

This line has a slope of 1 and cuts the y-axis at \( y = k \). Every such line can be uniquely determined by different values of \( k \), which are differences \( y_0 - x_0 \) for various points \((x_0, y_0)\). Each equivalence class corresponds to a different line parallel to the line \( y = x \).

Hence, the equivalence classes under this relation are all lines of the form \( y = x + k \) where \( k \) is a constant, and each line represents a unique equivalence class.


